[{"id":"VR870001","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:A part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"A\">\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\"><strong>Part A</strong></p>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\"><span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Indicate</span> whether the magnitude of the acceleration of the bar increases, decreases, or stays the same as the bar begins moving down the rails, by writing one of the following:&nbsp;</p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li class=\"stem_paragraph\">Increases</li>\n\t<li class=\"stem_paragraph\">Decreases</li>\n\t<li class=\"stem_paragraph\">Stays the same</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\"><span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Justify</span> your response. Your justification may reference equations but must include conceptual reasoning beyond algebraic solutions.&nbsp;</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"item_part part_id:B part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"B\">\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\"><strong>Part B</strong></p>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Some time after its release, the bar is moving with speed v down the rails. <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Derive</span> an equation for the acceleration of the bar in terms of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"m\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"m\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>m</mi></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"l\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"l\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mo>ℓ</mo></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"theta\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"theta\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>θ</mi></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"B\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"B\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>B</mi></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"R\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"R\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>R</mi></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"v\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"v\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>v</mi></math></span></span>, and physical constants, as appropriate. Begin your derivation by writing a fundamental physics principle or an equation from the reference information.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"item_part part_id:C part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"C\">\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\"><strong>Part C</strong></p>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\"><span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Indicate</span> whether your equation for the acceleration of the bar derived in part B is consistent with your reasoning in part A.&nbsp; Briefly <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">justify</span> your answer.&nbsp;</p>\n</div>\n","rubricRef":"VR870001_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<p class=\"direction_paragraph\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">A conducting bar of mass <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"m\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"m\" overflow=\"scroll\"> <mi>m</mi> </math></span></span> is placed on two long conducting rails a distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"l\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"l\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mo>ℓ</mo></math></span></span> apart. The rails are inclined at an angle <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"theta\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"theta\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>θ</mi></math></span></span> with respect to the horizontal and the bar is able to slide on the rails with negligible friction between the bar and rails. The bar and rails are in a uniform and constant magnetic field of magnitude <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"B\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"B\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>B</mi></math></span></span> oriented perpendicular to the rails. A resistor of resistance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"R\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"R\" overflow=\"scroll\"> <mi>R</mi> </math></span></span> connects the upper ends of the rails and completes the circuit, as shown. The bar is released from rest at the top of the incline.</p>\n&nbsp;\n\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows two long conducting rails inclined at an angle of theta from the horizontal, such that they point downward and to the right. The rods are parallel and a distance l apart. A conducting bar is laid horizontally across the rails and perpendicular to them. The tops of the rails are connected by a wire that contains a resistor with resistance R.  A magnetic field of magnitude B is in the region between the two long conducting rails, and points upward and to the right, perpendicular to the plane of the long conducting rails.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR870001.g03.svg\" /></div>\n"}]}]